Kazmi","reviewer_id":"118413994480873852559","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/118413994480873852559?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"An Unforgettable Night Out in the Cameron Highlands

We had an absolutely fantastic time at the Cameron Highlands night market. It's not just for families, but a vibrant hub for everyone--couples, solo travelers, and groups of friends will all find something to love. The atmosphere is electric, and it's truly a must-visit on a weekend trip.
The food options were the real star of the show. We came hungry and left completely satisfied! Besides the incredible pakoras, we were spoiled for choice with a huge variety of street food. The aroma of grilled BBQ skewers and juicy burgers filled the air, and we couldn't resist trying some. The roasted corn and sweet potato/yam were perfect for a cold evening, and we loved how many different kinds of Malaysian street food were available. It's a true foodie's paradise.
Beyond the prepared food, the market is a treasure trove of local goods. We were amazed at the stalls selling fresh vegetables brought directly by the farmers, offering a genuine taste of the region's produce. We also found some amazing honey stalls, which are a great place to pick up a sweet souvenir.
Shopping here is just as much fun as eating. We browsed countless stalls selling everything from unique Cameron Highlands-labeled T-shirts, socks, and gloves to charming keychains. We even got custom engraved keychains with our names, which made for a great personalized memento. The variety of plants, especially the many types of cacti, was also fascinating to see.
The entire market buzzes with a cool, lively energy. It's the perfect place to experience the local culture, interact with friendly vendors, and enjoy the cool mountain air. Whether you're looking for delicious food, unique souvenirs, or just a fun and authentic local experience, this market delivers. I would highly recommend it to all tourists coming here on the weekend--it's an experience you won't forget.","published_at":"a month * A stunning place to visit with a wide range of things to explore; from food to souvenirs, fresh produce, clothes, toys, etc.
* The atmosphere is vibrant and bustling making it a real highlight of Cameron Highlands.
* Large variety of food stalls offering local and street-style options.
* Prices are still generally reasonable despite it being a tourist spot.
* We especially loved the cactus booth and personally picked up quite a few lovely little pots.

Cons:
* Only one way in and out of the area, so traffic can be a nightmare during weekends or public holidays. Planning ahead is crucial.
* Open-air parking available at RM3 per entry, but it fills up quickly during peak times.
* If it rains, it's unfortunately kinda game over. The market is fully outdoors, and the parking area can become muddy and unpleasant.
* Could really benefit from having more rubbish bins placed around the market to help with litter control.

Personal Thoughts:
* It's certainly worth a visit, especially if it's your first time. Plenty to see, eat, and buy; from snacks to souvenirs.

Tan","reviewer_id":"113189277262231186781","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/113189277262231186781?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"I recently had the opportunity to explore the famous Cameron Highlands Night Market, a vibrant and lively spot that perfectly captures the essence of this unique hill station.

Located in Brinchang, this night market is a must-visit for anyone looking to experience the local flavors and culture of Cameron Highlands.

The market is usually bustling with activity, filled with stalls offering a wide range of products, from fresh local produce to delicious street food and handcrafted souvenirs.

One of the things that struck me most about this market is its atmosphere. As you stroll through the bustling lanes, you're greeted with the aromatic scent of freshly grilled corn, sweet strawberries, and local delicacies like steamboat skewers and fried sweet potatoes.

The variety of food options is truly impressive, catering to every palate. I particularly enjoyed the fried mushrooms and the local sweet potato balls, which were crispy on the outside and soft on the inside--perfect for a cool, misty evening.

The market also offers a glimpse into the local lifestyle and traditions. It's a place where you can see families enjoying their time together, tourists eagerly sampling different foods, and vendors enthusiastically showcasing their products.

I found it fascinating to interact with the stall owners, who were more than happy to share stories about their produce and the history of the market.

Despite its popularity, the night market retains a local charm that's hard to find in more commercialized tourist spots.

I recommend visiting early to avoid the crowd and to get the freshest picks, especially if you're looking to buy some of the region's famous tea, honey, or strawberries.

Overall, the Cameron Highlands Night Market offers a perfect blend of flavors, culture, and community spirit.

It's a place where you can truly experience the heart and soul of Cameron Highlands.

amirul","reviewer_id":"108859627853030152199","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/108859627853030152199?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Pasar Malam Brinchang in Cameron Highlands is an incredible night market that offers a unique shopping and dining experience. One of the best things about this market is the amazing selection of fresh produce, including strawberries, corn, and vegetables that are sourced directly from local farms.

The strawberries at Pasar Malam Brinchang are some of the sweetest and most delicious that you'll ever taste. They are hand-picked and brought to the market each night, so you can be sure that you're getting the freshest fruit possible. Whether you enjoy them on their own or in a delicious strawberry dessert, you won't be disappointed.

The corn at Pasar Malam Brinchang is also incredibly fresh and delicious. The vendors at the market grill the corn to perfection, creating a smoky flavor that pairs perfectly with the natural sweetness of the corn. It's the perfect snack to enjoy while you stroll through the market.

Finally, the fresh vegetables at Pasar Malam Brinchang are a true highlight of the market. From leafy greens to crunchy carrots and colorful peppers, there is no shortage of delicious and healthy options to choose from. Whether you're a vegetarian or just looking to add some nutritious options to your diet, you'll find everything you need at this market.

Overall, Pasar Malam Brinchang is a must-visit for anyone who loves fresh produce and delicious food. With its incredible selection of strawberries, corn, and vegetables, as well as its bustling atmosphere and friendly vendors, it's a market that you won't soon forget. Be sure to stop by and experience it for yourself!","published_at":"2 years The Pasar Malam in Cameron Highlands opens as early as 5 PM, and we visited on our first day. Unfortunately, we were quite disappointed. The stalls sell mostly the same items repetitively: strawberries, sweet potatoes, vegetables, and drinks. There wasn't much of a "wow" factor despite the hype in the reviews.

On the positive side, the strawberries here are a cheap deal, and there is paid parking nearby for RM3 per entry, which is convenient to avoid parking issues. I tried the only char kuey teow available, and it was pretty good. However, the rest of the offerings were just so-so.

S","reviewer_id":"115867102249633995566","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115867102249633995566?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"Although this listing is for the riverside night market, I am actually going to write about a few of the bigger night markets in Kuantan. A night market or `pasar malam' is a street market (a street is actually closed off to vehicles for the evening, and stalls are set up on the street itself) which starts at around 4.30pm and runs till around 10pm.

There are different locations around Kuantan:
1. Riverside (near Taman Gelora) on Sundays
2. UTC car park in the middle of town (near the stadium) on Saturdays
3. Indera Mahkota 2, behind the Tengku Ampuan Afzan mosque on Fridays

The stalls sell mainly food & beverages. Many are prepared and cooked on site, so even if you don't want to buy food, it'll be interesting enough to observe and to take colourful photos. But really......you can't possibly be going to a night market without trying the food! There are various types of rice - nasi kerabu, nasi minyak, nasi berlauk, nasi ayam. Various types of noodles - fried noodles, laksa, noodles with soup. Various types of local cakes or kueh. Various beverages - sugarcane, soya bean milk, coconut water, and even ice-blended mocha!

Besides food and drinks, there are a few stalls selling raw cooking items like fresh vegetables, fish, chicken and also food stalls.

Whenever i travel, I try to go to a local market. It tells a lot about the people in that place. So definitely try visiting a pasar malam in kuantan. I personally prefer the one in Indera Mahkota 2. There is a bus from town that stops at the Tengku Ampuan Afzan mosque. I think it's the number 301. I finally did so last weekend (27/7). It was a GREAT experience, and YES, it was definitely long! We arrived early (before 7am) but got stuck in the area because the traders had set up/were setting up their stalls at that time. We finally got out from the ruckus 20 minutes later. Well, we're still early and managed to get the freshest produce from the market. I got some fresh produce for my bubur lambuk (paku merah and daun kaduk). I also bought a bunch of young green ferns for my paku sambal belacan and a bunch of ulam raja to be had with steamed rice. Other than these, I bought a lot of traditional Pahang yummies like kuih pepena, kuih beko kelapa, tepung gomak, lepat ubi, laksam, laksa pahang, and kuih tepung bungkus. Others in my group bought other yummies like martabak daging (super thick and yumms), tapai ubi, laksa penang, and many others. Between us, we bought a lot of petai, ulam2an, kerepek, udang galah (yes, they had the freshest and cheapest seafood!), traditional kuihs, fresh produce like lemongrass, asam keping, coffee and more. We spent about 2 hours at the market. It was a 2-hour walk well spent. I wouldn't mind going here again for the experience and the freshest ever produce.","published_at":"3 months The car boot sale outside Masjid Negeri Pahang in Kuantan is a vibrant and festive market that is a must-visit for anyone in the area. This bustling nighttime bazaar offers an incredible range of items--from food and drinks to clothes, toys, and delightful knick-knacks. Every stall is a discovery, and the festive atmosphere makes shopping here a real pleasure.

The location, right in the heart of Kuantan's lively night scene, adds to the charm, making it a perfect spot for an evening out. The food options are a particular highlight, with an array of traditional fried treats alongside trendy cakes, cookies, and a variety of refreshing fruit juices. Each vendor brings something unique to the table, both in terms of goods and the warmth of service.

Whether you're a local or just passing through, the car boot sale offers a slice of local culture coupled with the excitement of finding hidden gems. Highly recommended for a fun and fulfilling outing!","published_at":"a year Lee","reviewer_id":"109397825257995094119","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/109397825257995094119?hl=en-GB","rating":3,"review_text":"Haven been to a jight market for long and found out about this when I wanted to go somewhere on a Thursday night and realized that this place is open.
It's not hard to get there, pretty close to an MRT station,  few stops away from downtown like Bukit Bintang can get there within 30 minutes.
It's quite a happening place, and there was a lot of variety of food. The food sold is quite diverse and you don't really see repeats so it was worth the effort to walk from one end to another, not very long if you were to just walk workout stopping then it's 5 minutes.
Recommended that you start walking from one end where the shopping mall is to the other end, then make a you turn back. In this way you would have seen all the stalls then decide what to buy as you make your way back.
Some of the stuff looks pretty good, with pretty reasonable prices. I saw one which caught my attention, it was the one selling the salted egg dishes, think it's called Ultraman or something. Looked good and the food was like cooked in front of your eyes. I decided to buy and was a regret that it tasted cold, and it was quite expensive ordering a mixed bag.
The one I ordered and I liked was the mee jian kueh (also known as Kam Long bao) and the yam dessert. It was good, cheap and filling.
Love these night markets you can  just get yourself full without a hole in the pocket.","published_at":"a year A lot of empty spaces too. Reviews and articles by travel bloggers about \"Bentong Walk\" are all hyped and grossly inaccurate, and totally irresponsible as they are a misrepresentation to domestic and foreign tourists. As a fairly avid traveller, my take is that Malaysia is such a beautiful country with unmatched culinary delights that fit most palates but has a lonnnng way to go in cleaning up and in developing and maintaining quality tourism products/services/facilities and stepping up level of customer service. There's just been too many disappointments from over-sold and over-hyped \"attractions\" in the country. The ministry of  Tourism, Arts & Culture needs to get to work! Tourism is more than putting up fancy lightings and colourful decorations. The vicinity is small but it has lots to offer. Fresh durian, fruits, vege and of course ginger! Some locals shared must try their ginger ailment, taufupok, kicap, sek kei ma, toast with kaya and butter. I totally love the local coffee. Rich in flavours, creamy and not overly sweet overshadowing the coffee.

A local added that prices for durian is higher on weekends. But still we found fresh, big durian and happy to pay the price. People are friendly. Parking on the roadside was free or so it seemed as no one put up their parking coupon. And we didn't get any summon. It was a Saturday.

Since our weather is usually hot and humid it would be nice if we could find some cafes with another round of coffee and air conditioning. Too bad we didn't find one. We had our brunch in kopitiam. Pan mee and coffee. They even allowed us to order next door as well. "No outside food and drinks" non existence in here?
